the government sunday approved a draft 4667 
billion budget for fiscal 1990 that for the first time in 15 years 
does not rely on deficitfinancing bonds 
the cabinet held a special meeting to accept the finance 
ministrys draft budget for the fiscal year beginning in march the 
budget represents a 97 percent increase over current spending 
it calls for increases of 55 percent in defense spending to 
291 billion 59 percent in aid to developing countries to about 
56 billion and 62 percent in social security spending to 815 
billion 
the increases reflect growing tax revenues flowing from japans 
booming economy which just entered its fourth year of continuous 
expansion 
further negotiations will finetune specific allocations for the 
final version of the budget which is expected to be approved 
friday 
the cabinet also approved a supplementary budget for the current 
fiscal year the 415 billion budget is the largest stopgap 
budget ever 
the greatest thrust of this years budget is the desire of the 
government to end its dependence on deficitfinancing bonds a 
foreign ministry official said speaking on condition of anonymity 
since they were first introduced in 1975 we have made earnest 
efforts to end this dependency we were finally able to rid 
ourselves of this unhealthy system 
the government issued 93 billion worth of deficitfinancing 
bonds last year to cover the budgets red ink that amount will be 
made up in part by an infusion in fiscal 1990 of 915 billion from 
government sales last year of its shares in nippon telegraph and 
telephone corp as well as increased tax revenues the official 
said 
defense spending will rise to 291 billion but because of 
economic expansion the defense budget will dip below 1 percent of 
japans gross national product for the first time in four years 
standing at 0991 percent of the gnp 
in the mid1970s japan adopted a policy of keeping defense 
spending to within 1 percent of the gnp but since 1986 it has 
hovered just above that figure 
spending on public works will rise 03 percent to 438 billion 
next fiscal year although the united states has urged japan to 
increase such publicly funded projects to help ease tokyos trade 
surplus with washington the marginal increase is sufficient 
the finance ministry official said 
the draft budget was compiled on the basis of government 
estimates that the economy will grow an inflationadjusted 4 
percent next year a brisk pace despite a slowdown from the 
estimated 46 percent growth in fiscal 1989 
