corp sees connecticuts investment as the last hurdle before new 
owners can take over the troubled gunmaker 
borges said state officials have several concerns about joining 
the buyout including a declining world market for handguns and the 
possibility of new gun control legislation that could hamper the 
new company 
however borges said this does not mean we wont get to a 
point where we have something acceptable and he added that talks 
were continuing 
colt industries put the firearms division on the market last 
spring and agreed in late november to sell the division to cf 
holdings in a deal that was to include the state as a shareholder 
cf holdings includes anthony autorino former president of 
united technologies hamilton standard division and now president 
of shared technologies in wethersfield conn richard f gamble 
another former hamilton standard president and ronald f stilwell 
colt firearms vice president for military sales 
the price of the deal was never disclosed but analysts estimated 
it could range from 50 million to 200 million the state has 
refused to disclose the size of its possible investment in the 
project 
autorino said the investor group was becoming anxious about the 
states hesitation 
we have a firm price and an agreement and times getting 
short he said 
one obstacle to completing the sale was removed earlier this 
week when the united auto workers and the investors who would run 
the plant agreed to a full settlement of the 3yearold uawcolt 
strike and endorsed a contract to return to work 
the union was supposed to be the last hurdle in the deal 
said philip wheeler chief negotiator fo uaw local 376 that was 
the agreement and everybody was happy the union settled this deal 
should be done now 
wheeler would not disclose the details of the strike settlement 
and the new union contract friday because financing for the deal 
is still pending 
this is a difficult situation but as far as we are concerned 
we had an agreement with the state wheeler said we are still 
confident borges will finalize the deal the deal is still 
sound 
